[5] India (Pimpri-Chinchwad)
Date: Tue 16 Oct 2007
Source: ExpressIndia.com [edited]
<http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/40-more-dengue-cases-in-PimpriChinchwad/229052/>


Dengue and malaria cases continue to trouble residents in
Pimpri-Chinchwad. In the last 6 days since Newsline reported the
figures, 40 new dengue and 31 malaria cases have been reported. In
the last 9 and 1/2 months, the official dengue cases have thus
reached 228, while malaria cases are put at 536. So far, 4 persons
have died of dengue and 3 of malaria.

Unofficially, dengue cases are put at over 450, while malaria cases
are said to have crossed the 1000 mark. "This is because 264 private
hospitals and 500 dispensaries do not report the cases to us. There
are very few private hospitals who keep us regularly updated," say
health department officials of the Pimpri-Chinchwad Municipal Corporation.

Health officials said most of the dengue and malaria cases have been
reported from construction sites. Pimple Saudagar, Rahatni, Wakad and
Indryani Nagar are the areas where a large number of dengue and
malaria cases are recorded.

"Construction sites, where cesspools and collection of fresh water in
ponds are common, are the breeding grounds of dengue and malaria,"
says PCMC health director Dr Rajshekhar Iyer, pointing out that the
brisk construction activity in these suburbs was spawning dengue and malaria.

The health department, says Dr Iyer, has been on a massive awareness
campaign in residential areas and the Pimpri-Chinchwad-Bhosari industrial belt.

"Builders have also been issued notices to remove pools of water and
take care of the health of their workers," he said, adding that
anti-larval measures and fogging operations have been in full swing
across the country. Last week, the health department had hired
artists to perform street plays for spreading awareness about dengue,
malaria and keeping surroundings clean.

Health chief Dr Nagkumar Kunachgi said the 3-seat rickshaws would
soon be introduced for collecting garbage in residential areas. "This
will ensure that no garbage is found littered in busy residential
areas," he said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Collection of garbage may be somewhat helpful in reducing _Aedes_
mosquito breeding sites, but success in eliminating larval habitats
to control dengue virus vectors will be in houses and other
buildings, where a variety of water catchments are certain to occur.

Pimpri-Chinchwad, with a population of over one million, is a twin
city of Pune, located in Maharastra state in SW India. A map of India
can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/india_pol01.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[6] Sri Lanka (Kandy)
Date: Thu 18 Oct 2007
Source: Daily News [edited]
<http://www.dailynews.lk/2007/10/18/news33.asp>


Kandy Municipal Corporation Chief Medical Officer Dr. Asoka Senarath
said that 28 suspected dengue cases have been detected in the Kandy
Municipal area this year [2007].

Dr. Senarath, who warned that there is a possibility of the disease
raising its head with the onset of current rains, said the council
needed the assistance and co-operation of the public in the area to combat it.

He said 112 suspected dengue patients had been treated at the Kandy
General Hospital during the last 10 months of this year [2007]. The
incidence this year is much less compared to last year [2006].

Meanwhile, the Kandy MC Medical Health unit conducted a door to door
public awareness campaign about dengue in the Kandy Municipal area
yesterday [17 Oct 2007] assisted by students of the Kandy D.S.
Senanayake Vidyalaya, St. Sylvester's College and Wariyapola
Sumangala Vidyalaya.

[Byline: Asela Kuruluwansa]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED would appreciate information about the laboratory
confirmation (or not) of these suspected dengue virus infections.

Kandy is located in the center of Sri Lanka, and a map can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/sri_lanka_pol01.jpg>.
