[7] Pakistan (Karachi)
Date: 18 Oct 2007
Source: The Post.com [edited]
<http://thepost.com.pk/NatNewsT.aspx?dtlid=123693&catid=2>


The Sindh Health Department's Monitoring Cell here Wednesday [17 Oct
2007] confirmed 3 more dengue fever induced deaths in the city,
bringing the total number of expired to 11.

Additional Health Secretary and Coordinator of the Cell Dr Shakil
Malik said 2 deaths, one each, were reported from Liaquat National
Hospital and Civil Hospital, Karachi on Tuesday [16 Oct 2007] and one
from Liaquat National Monday [15 Oct 2007].

"The number of dengue patients since 1 Aug 2007 has turned out to be
937, including 416 positive," Dr Shakil Malik said. More than 25 were
said to be hospitalised at different healthcare facilities, both
private and public sectors, across the city.

EDO - Health, Karachi City District Government, and Dr SA Sanjnani
said the city government was aware of the emerging situation.

All CDG-K healthcare facilities were said to be well equipped to
handle the situation.

"We are already engaged in regular fogging and fumigation of all
parts of the city to destroy breeding points and now are ensuring
provision for dengue fever tests and other relevant facilities to the
people," he elaborated.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Fumigation and fogging are likely to provide only temporary
reduction in the adult _Aedes_ mosquito population in the absence of
elimination of breeding sites, which is not mentioned.

A map of Pakistan can be accessed at healthmap:
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=30,69.4,5> and at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/pakistan_pol_2002.jpg>.

The WHO (World Health Organization) description of dengue fever and
the more deadly dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF] can be found in
ProMED-mail's "Dengue/DHF update 20070514.1541." ProMED-mail thanks
the contributors to this update and encourages others to contribute
reports also. - Mod.TY]
